resources.string:
Exploitation of results:

 From the measurements obtained, the Ruffier index (Ri) as well as the Ruffier-Dickson index (Di) are calculated:

 Ri = (p0 + p1 + p2 - 200) / 10;
 Di = ((p1 - 70) + 2 * (p2 - p0)) / 10;

 Interpretation :

Ruffier index (Ri) :
 - Ri < 0: very good adaptation to effort;
 - Ri ≥ 0 et < 5: good adaptation to effort;
 - Ri ≥ 5 et < 10: average adaptation to effort;
 - Ri ≥ 10 et < 15: insufficient adaptation to effort;
 - Ri ≥ 15: poor adaptation to the effort, an additional medical assessment is necessary.


Ruffier-Dickson index (Di) :
 - Di < 0: excellent;
 - Di ≥ 0 et < 2: really good;
 - Di ≥ 2 et < 4: good;
 - Di ≥ 4 et < 6: average;
 - Di ≥ 6 et < 8: weak;
 - Di ≥ 8 et < 10: really weak;
 - Di ≥ 10: poor adaptation to the effort.
